articleBody">On Wed, Jul 14, 2010 at 4:09 PM, Andi Kleen &lt;andi&#64;firstfloor.org&gt; wrote:<br />&gt;<br />&gt; It can happen in theory, but for such a rare case take a lock<br />&gt; and walking everything should be fine.<br /><br />Actually, that's _exactly_ the wrong kind of thinking.<br /><br />Bad latency is bad latency, even when it happens rarely. So latency<br />problems kill - even when they are rare. So you want to avoid them.<br />And walking every possible page table is a _huge_ latency problem when<br />it happens.<br /><br />In contrast, what's the advantage of doing thigns synchronously while<br />holding a lock? It's that you can avoid a few page faults, and get<br />better CPU use. But that's _stupid_ if it's something that is very<br />rare to begin with.<br /><br />So the very rarity argues for the lazy approach. If it wasn't rare,<br />there would be a much stronger argument for trying to do things<br />up-front.<br /><br />                   Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
